                "eatingPlate": {
                    "slides": [
                        {
                            "title": "Your Plate is Your Daily Medicine",
                            "text": "Every time you eat, you're either feeding disease or fighting it. The good news? You don't need expensive foods or complicated recipes. You just need to know what belongs on your plate-and how much space it should take up. Let's build your healthiest plate together.",
                            "myth": "\u2753 'Healthy eating means giving up my culture's food'-MYTH. Traditional foods from Brazil, Mexico, Central/South America can be incredibly healthy. We're optimizing what you already know, not replacing it.",
                            "lesson": "This plate method works for breakfast, lunch, and dinner. Works for Brazilian food, Mexican food, American food-ANY food. Once you see this pattern, you can make healthier choices anywhere-even at a friend's barbecue or a birthday party."
                        },
                        {
                            "title": "Half Your Plate-Vegetables (The Foundation Builders)",
                            "text": "Half your plate should be vegetables-that's about 2 cups, or roughly the size of TWO of your fists side-by-side. Vegetables are your foundation repair crew-they fight inflammation, stabilize blood sugar, and protect your kidneys and heart. The more COLOR variety, the better.",
                            "myth": "\u2753 'Vegetables are expensive'-TRY THIS: Frozen vegetables are just as nutritious as fresh and often much cheaper. Canned vegetables are OK if you rinse them well.",
                            "lesson": "If you only change ONE thing about your meals, make it this: fill half your plate with vegetables before you add anything else. This one change protects all three of your body's systems.",
                            "details": {
                                "excellent": "Dark Leafy Greens (Couve, Spinach, Chard), Cruciferous (Broccoli, Cauliflower, Cabbage), Colorful Peppers, Tomatoes.",
                                "veryGood": "Carrots, Beets, Jicama, Green beans, Squash (Zucchini, Chuchu).",
                                "good": "Corn (limit to 1/2 cup), Peas, Green Plantains.",
                                "cultural": "\ud83c\udde7\ud83c\uddf7 Couve, Chuchu, Jil\u00f3, Maxixe. \ud83c\udf2e Nopales, Chiles, Tomatillos, Calabacitas."
                            }
                        },
                        {
                            "title": "Quarter of Your Plate-Protein (The Repair Workers)",
                            "text": "One quarter of your plate is protein-about the size of a deck of cards, or the palm of your hand. Protein builds and repairs your muscles, keeps you full, and doesn't spike your blood sugar like carbs can. The TYPE of protein matters for your heart and kidneys.",
                            "myth": "\u2753 'I need red meat every day for strength'-MYTH. Fish, chicken, beans, and eggs provide all the protein you need with much less strain on your heart and kidneys.",
                            "lesson": "Every time you choose fish or beans over red meat, you're protecting your heart and kidneys. Small swaps add up to big protection over time.",
                            "details": {
                                "excellent": "Fatty Fish (Salmon, Sardines), Beans (Black, Pinto, Kidney), Lentils, Chickpeas, Eggs.",
                                "veryGood": "Chicken/Turkey (skinless), Pork Loin (lean), Tofu/Tempeh.",
                                "limit": "Red Meat (Beef, Lamb), Processed Meats (Sausage, Bacon, Deli meats).",
                                "cultural": "\ud83c\udde7\ud83c\uddf7 Feij\u00e3o, Bacalhau, Frango Grelhado. \ud83c\udf2e Frijoles, Ceviche, Grilled Tacos."
                            }
                        },
                        {
                            "title": "Quarter of Your Plate-Whole Grains & Healthy Carbs",
                            "text": "The last quarter of your plate is your energy source-whole grains and healthy carbs. This is about the size of your cupped hand or a tennis ball. The TYPE of carb makes a huge difference for your blood sugar.",
                            "myth": "\u2753 'Carbs are the enemy'-NO. White, refined carbs spike sugar. Whole grains digest slowly and give steady energy. Don't quit carbs, just swap for brown rice, sweet potatoes, or whole wheat.",
                            "lesson": "You don't have to give up rice or tortillas-just adjust portions. Mix white rice with brown rice or cauliflower rice to start the transition.",
                            "details": {
