                                "veryGood": "Yuca (Mandioca), Green Plantain, Corn Tortillas, Whole Wheat Pasta.",
                                "limit": "White Rice, White Bread, Sugary drinks, Fried starches (French fries).",
                                "cultural": "\ud83c\udde7\ud83c\uddf7 Mandioca, Farofa (small amounts), P\u00e3o de Queijo (treat). \ud83c\udf2e Frijoles, Corn Tortillas, Yuca."
                            }
                        },
                        {
                            "title": "What About Drinks? (The Hidden Sugar Problem)",
                            "text": "What you DRINK can wreck an otherwise healthy meal. One can of soda has 10 teaspoons of sugar-more than your body should have in an entire day. Even 100% fruit juice is liquid sugar without the fiber.",
                            "myth": "\u2753 'Fruit juice is healthy because it's natural'-INCORRECT. Without the fiber of the whole fruit, juice spikes your blood sugar as fast as soda. Eat the fruit, drink the water.",
                            "lesson": "Switching from one daily soda to water cuts 140,000 calories per year. Your blood sugar, kidneys, and heart will feel the difference almost immediately."
                        },
                        {
                            "title": "Putting It All Together-Sample Healthy Plates",
                            "text": "The plate method works for ANY cuisine. Same proportions, different foods. Whether it's a Brazilian lunch, Mexican dinner, or American breakfast, the 50/25/25 rule keeps you protected.",
                            "myth": "\u2753 'My family will think I'm on a diet'-REDEFINE IT. You're eating like your ancestors did-many vegetables, beans every day, sustainable protein. This is wisdom, not a fad.",
                            "lesson": "Don't cook separate meals. Make the same food for the family, just adjust YOUR plate proportions. You lead by example."
                        },
                        {
                            "title": "Fruits-Nature's Candy (The Sweet Truth)",
                            "text": "Fruit is healthy-but it's nature's dessert. Whole fruits have fiber that slows sugar absorption, while juice and dried fruit hit your blood sugar like candy. Aim for 2-3 servings of whole fruit daily.",
                            "myth": "\u2753 'I can eat unlimited fruit'-NO. Fruit contains fructose (natural sugar). If you have diabetes, focus on berries and citrus which have less sugar and more fiber.",
                            "lesson": "Swap juice for a whole orange. You'll feel fuller, get the fiber, and protect your metabolism from the sugar rush."
                        },
                        {
                            "title": "Healthy Fats-A Little Goes a Long Way",
                            "text": "Your body NEEDS fat-but the type matters. Healthy fats (olive oil, avocado, nuts) protect your heart. Unhealthy fats (fried foods, lard, butter) damage it. Even healthy fats are high in calories, so keep portions small.",
                            "myth": "\u2753 'Avoid all fat for heart health'-WRONG. Saturated fats are the problem. Unsaturated fats from plants and fish are actually medicine for your blood vessels.",
                            "lesson": "One tablespoon of oil is 120 calories. Measure your oil instead of pouring freely. You'll cut hundreds of calories without losing flavor."
                        },
                        {
                            "title": "Your Weekly Meal Framework",
                            "text": "You don't need to be perfect every meal. Consistency beats perfection. Aim for 15-18 'Healthy Plate' meals per week. Plan for the other 3-6 meals to be flexible for social events or treats.",
                            "myth": "\u2753 'Healthy meals take too long to cook'-REPLAN. Sunday prep (2 hours) can save 10 hours during the week. Frozen veggies take 4 minutes. Healthy can be fast.",
                            "lesson": "One unhealthy meal doesn't erase a week of healthy choices. If you slip up, return to the plate method at your very next meal. No shame, just progress."
                        },
                        {
                            "title": "Your Action Plan-Start Today",
                            "text": "Don't try to change everything tomorrow. Pick ONE change this week-like swapping soda for water or adding one veggie serving. Small changes stick; big overhauls often fail.",
                            "myth": "\u2753 'I've failed at diets before'-BECAUSE diets are temporary. This is a new normal that fits YOUR life and YOUR culture. Marathons are won one step at a time.",
                            "lesson": "You have the power to repair your foundation and protect your heart and kidneys. We're here to support you in every small win. You've got this."
                        }
                    ]
                },
