                "movementExplorer": {
                    "title": "Move More, Live Better",
                    "next": "Next Slide",
                    "prev": "Previous",
                    "slides": [
                        {
                            "title": "Why Your Body Needs Movement-The CKM Connection",
                            "text": "When you move your muscles, something incredible happens: your muscle cells open up tiny doors that let glucose (blood sugar) rush in WITHOUT needing insulin. Your muscles literally drink the sugar from your blood. This happens whether you have diabetes or not, whether you're taking medication or not. Movement is the ONLY thing that works this way-it's your secret weapon for CKM health that costs nothing and works every single time.",
                            "lesson": "Your muscles are like sponges for blood sugar. Even a 10-minute walk after dinner can drop your blood sugar by 20-40 points-that's better than some medications!"
                        },
                        {
                            "title": "The Two Types of Movement You Need",
                            "text": "Your body needs two types of maintenance. CARDIO (walking, dancing) is like changing the oil in your car-it keeps your heart and blood vessels running smoothly. STRENGTH (lifting, carrying) is like maintaining your house's structure-it builds the muscles that soak up blood sugar. You need both for complete CKM health.",
                            "lesson": "You don't need a gym. Carrying groceries, playing with grandkids, or walking to the store all count toward your CKM goals."
                        },
                        {
                            "title": "Starting from ZERO-Your First Month",
                            "text": "If you're currently doing NO exercise, you start with FIVE MINUTES. Yes, seriously. Five minutes of movement is infinitely better than zero. We'll build up to the goal of 150 minutes per week over 3 months.",
                            "lesson": "Goal Week 1-2: 5 min, 3-4 days. Goal Week 3-4: 10 min, 4-5 days. Progress, not perfection."
                        },
                        {
                            "title": "Cardio Mastery-Finding Your 'Zone 2' Sweet Spot",
                            "text": "The 'sweet spot' is Zone 2-where you're breathing harder and can feel yourself working, but you could keep going for an hour. This is where your body burns fat most efficiently and builds the cellular machinery (mitochondria) that reverses insulin resistance.",
                            "lesson": "Use the 'Talk Test': You're in Zone 2 if you can speak full sentences but have to take a breath mid-sentence occasionally. If you can sing, speed up. If you can't talk, slow down."
                        },
                        {
                            "title": "Strength Training Without a Gym-Bodyweight Basics",
                            "text": "Muscle is your body's best blood sugar storage unit. Every pound of muscle you build creates more 'sponge' to soak up glucose. Your own body weight provides perfect resistance. These exercises work every major muscle group and can be done in your living room in 15-20 minutes.",
                            "lesson": "Start with 1 set of 8-10 reps: Wall Push-Ups, Bodyweight Squats, Glute Bridges, Plank, and Lunges. Do this 2-3 times per week."
                        },
                        {
                            "title": "Fitting Movement into Real Life (MA Seasons)",
                            "text": "You don't need an hour at the gym. 3 x 10-minute sessions = same benefit as 1 x 30-minute session. In Massachusetts, weather is a barrier. Use indoor 'mall walking' at Natick Mall or Shoppers World during winter, or free YouTube walking videos at home.",
                            "lesson": "November-March: Go INDOORS. Malls are free, warm, and safe. Walking at home to a video works just as well. Don't risk falling on ice!"
                        },
                        {
                            "title": "Overcoming Real Barriers",
                            "text": "Money, time, pain, and safety are REAL obstacles. If you have joint pain, try low-impact water walking or chair exercises. If time is tight, use 'movement snacks' (stairs, parking farther away). If safety is a concern, walk with a friend or use indoor options.",
                            "lesson": "For every barrier, there's a solution. No gym? Bodyweight is free. No time? Do 5-minute bursts. Exercise shouldn't create stress; it should relieve it."
                        },
                        {
                            "title": "Your Personalized Movement Plan",
                            "text": "No one-size-fits-all plan works for everyone. Your plan depends on your starting point and your specific goals. Follow our 12-week roadmap from zero to 150 minutes.",
                            "lesson": "Action for today: Walk for 5 minutes after dinner. That's your start. Track your progress, count your wins, and watch your numbers improve."
                        }
                    ]
                },
                "foodLabel": {
                    "title": "Label Detective",
                    "next": "Next",
                    "prev": "Back",
                    "slides": [
                        {
                            "title": "Introduction-Your Superpower at the Grocery Store",
                            "text": "Food companies want you confused. Packaging says 'natural,' 'healthy,' '100% real'-but what does that actually mean? The REAL information is in the small print: the Nutrition Facts label and ingredient list. Once you know how to read these, you have the power to choose foods that protect your CKM health instead of damaging it. It takes 30 seconds to check a label. Those 30 seconds can add years to your life.",
                            "lesson": "By the end of this module, you'll be able to walk into any grocery store and identify the healthiest options in 30 seconds or less. This is a skill you'll use for the rest of your life."
                        },
                        {
                            "title": "Anatomy of a Food Label-The #1 Mistake",
                            "text": "Here's the #1 mistake people make: they look at calories, sugar, or sodium-but they IGNORE the serving size. Everything on this label is PER SERVING, not per package. If you eat the whole package thinking 'only 100 calories!' but the package has 3 servings, you just ate 300 calories. Serving size is THE FIRST thing you check. Always.",
                            "lesson": "You don't need to memorize every number. Focus on serving size, sodium, added sugars, and fiber. Those four pieces of information tell you 90% of what you need to know.",
                            "hotspots": [
                                {
                                    "id": "servings-per",
                                    "title": "Servings Per Container",
                                    "text": "This package has 8 servings. If you eat half the package, multiply everything on the label by 4."
                                },
                                {
                                    "id": "serving-size",
                                    "title": "Serving Size",
                                    "text": "Everything below is for THIS AMOUNT ONLY. Companies choose small sizes to make products look healthier."
                                },
                                {
                                    "id": "calories",
                                    "title": "Calories",
                                    "text": "Energy per serving. 230 from beans = repair. 230 from soda = damage."
                                },
                                {
                                    "id": "fats",
                                    "title": "Fats",
                                    "text": "Saturated fat clogs wiring. Trans fat (aim for 0g) corrodes it."
                                },
                                {
                                    "id": "sodium",
                                    "title": "Sodium",
                                    "text": "The Water Magnet. Goal: <2000mg per day total. High sodium damages heart and kidneys."
                                },
                                {
                                    "id": "carbs",
                                    "title": "Total Carbohydrate",
                                    "text": "Includes fiber and sugars. This number affects your blood sugar most directly."
                                },
                                {
                                    "id": "fiber",
                                    "title": "Dietary Fiber",
                                    "text": "Your Metabolic Shield. Goal: 25-35g per day. Look for 3g+ per serving."
                                },
                                {
                                    "id": "added-sugar",
                                    "title": "Added Sugars",
                                    "text": "CRITICAL. Limit to <25g/day. One soda can often exceeds your entire day's allowance."
                                },
                                {
                                    "id": "protein",
                                    "title": "Protein",
                                    "text": "Helps metabolism but too much stresses kidneys. Balance is key."
                                }
                            ]
                        },
                        {
                            "title": "The % Daily Value-Your Cheat Sheet",
                            "text": "See those percentages on the right? They tell you if one serving has a little or a lot. FDA Rule: 5% or less is LOW. 20% or more is HIGH. Trick: You WANT 'HIGH' for fiber, protein, vitamins. You WANT 'LOW' for saturated fat, sodium, added sugars.",
                            "lesson": "Small percentages for the 'bad stuff' (sodium/sugar), big percentages for the 'good stuff' (fiber). No calculator needed.",
                            "table": [
                                {
                                    "n": "Dietary Fiber",
                                    "v": "20% \u2705",
                                    "m": "HIGH-Excellent! Protects all 3 systems."
                                },
                                {
                                    "n": "Sodium",
                                    "v": "25% \ud83d\udd34",
                                    "m": "HIGH-Caution! Damages heart and kidneys."
                                },
                                {
                                    "n": "Saturated Fat",
                                    "v": "10% \ud83d\udfe1",
                                    "m": "Moderate-Be careful."
                                },
                                {
                                    "n": "Added Sugars",
                                    "v": "40% \ud83d\udd34",
                                    "m": "HIGH-Way too much. Cracks foundation."
                                }
                            ]
                        },
                        {
                            "title": "Ingredient List-The Hidden Truth",
                            "text": "The ingredient list is in order by weight. If sugar is first, it's mostly sugar. Companies hide sugar under 60+ names (HFCS, dextrose, maltose). This is where you catch them lying.",
                            "lesson": "Front of package = marketing. Ingredient list = TRUTH. If you see ingredients you can't pronounce or multiple sugars, put it back.",
                            "rules": [
                                "First 3 ingredients: Should be whole foods, not sugar or refined flour.",
                                "Sugar Aliases: Watch for syrup, cane juice, maltodextrin, nectar.",
                                "Trans Fats: Avoid 'partially hydrogenated oil' entirely.",
                                "Whole Grains: Look for 'WHOLE wheat/oats' as the first ingredient."
                            ]
                        },
                        {
                            "title": "Label Detective-Real Comparisons",
                            "text": "Let's practice. Looking at real products shows how marketing can be deceptive. Sometimes 'healthy' versions are worse than regular ones.",
                            "lesson": "Low sodium beans, plain yogurt, corn tortillas-these save you money AND protect your health.",
                            "comparisons": [
                                {
                                    "name": "Black Beans",
                                    "a": "Regular: 460mg Sodium (20% DV) \ud83d\udd34",
                                    "b": "Low Sodium: 5mg Sodium \u2705",
                                    "win": "Goya Low Sodium"
                                },
                                {
                                    "name": "Bread",
                                    "a": "Generic Wheat: Refined flour, 1g fiber \u274c",
                                    "b": "100% Whole Wheat: 5g fiber, whole seeds \u2705",
                                    "win": "100% Whole Wheat"
                                },
                                {
                                    "name": "Yogurt",
                                    "a": "Strawberry: 13g Added Sugar (26% DV) \ud83d\udd34",
                                    "b": "Plain Greek + Berries: 0g Added Sugar, 3x Protein \u2705",
                                    "win": "Plain Greek + Fruit"
                                }
                            ]
                        },
                        {
                            "title": "Marketing Tricks-Decoding the Front",
                            "text": "FDA regulates the back, but barely regulates the front. Companies spend millions to trick you. 'Natural' means literally nothing legally.",
                            "lesson": "Never trust the front of the package. It's an advertisement. The facts are on the back.",
                            "claims": [
                                {
                                    "c": "'All Natural'",
                                    "t": "Meaningless. Arsenic is natural. Check the ingredients instead."
                                },
                                {
                                    "c": "'Heart Healthy'",
                                    "t": "Often ignores high sugar/sodium. Verify the Big 4 yourself."
                                },
                                {
                                    "c": "'Multigrain'",
                                    "t": "Could be multiple REFINED grains. Look for '100% Whole Grain'."
                                },
                                {
                                    "c": "'Sugar-Free'",
                                    "t": "Often adds extra fat or artificial sweeteners to compensate."
                                }
                            ]
                        },
                        {
                            "title": "Your 30-Second Reference Guide",
                            "text": "You can't memorize everything. Use the 'Big 4' method: (1) Added Sugars <5g, (2) Sodium <200mg, (3) Fiber>3g, (4) Saturated Fat <2g.",
                            "lesson": "Simple foods are cheaper and healthier. Beans, rice, oats, eggs, and frozen veggies are CKM champions.",
                            "flowchart": "Check Serving Size \u2192 Check Big 4 (Sugars, Sodium, Fiber, Fat) \u2192 Check Ingredients (First 3) \u2192 BUY or PUT BACK."
                        }
                    ],
                    "labels": {
                        "anatomy": "Anatomy",
                        "percentDV": "% Daily Value",
                        "ingredients": "Ingredients",
                        "marketing": "Marketing",
                        "shoppingGuide": "Guide",
                        "big3": "START WITH THE BIG 3: (1) Serving size, (2) Sodium, (3) Added sugars. Master these to be in the top 10% of shoppers."
                    }
                },
